<h1>Gnome Games</h1>
<p>
<strong><a href="http://git.gnome.org/browse/gnome-games/tree/lightsoff">Lights Off Source Code</a></strong><br/>
<strong><a href="http://git.gnome.org/browse/gnome-games/tree/swell-foop">Swell Foop Source Code</a></strong><br/>
<strong><a href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/hortont/3829466006/">Video of Mines</a></strong><br/>
<strong><a href="http://www.vimeo.com/2318879">[VERY OLD] Video of Lights Off</a></strong><br/>
<strong><a href="http://www.vimeo.com/3068796">[OLD] Video of Swell Foop</a></strong>

During GSoC'09, I worked on Gnome Games, completing and merging in two games (a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lights_Out_(game)">Lights Out</a> clone and a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SameGame">Same Game</a> clone) which were initially small scripts in the Seed <a href="http://git.gnome.org/browse/seed-examples/tree/">example tree</a>, and starting another game (a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minesweeper_(computer_game)">Minesweeper</a> clone).

